  "text": "In the present study, we examine the extent to which SES and CVD risk factors account for ethnic disparities in mortality rates observed in men and women in the Charleston Heart Study (CHS), a population based prospective cohort study begun in 1960. An earlier published study of the CHS cohort comparing 28-year all-cause mortality rates between white and black men suggests that SES accounts for most of the observed ethnic disparity in mortality among men, [CITATION_1] as did a 30-year follow-up analysis of both men and women in the CHS cohort. [CITATION_2] The present investigation extends the follow-up of this cohort for an additional 10-12 years and also includes data from women. The CHS provides an excellent opportunity to examine the influence of SES in a population-based cohort that contains a substantial proportion of blacks of varied SES and key baseline CVD risk factors, over a 40 year period.",
